snippet.textDisplay:
In battle rap, THE MOST IMPORTANT PART of battles, is the end, the handshake. On stage nothing you say has a ceiling, it is also common courtesy I've found to get in contact before hand with the person you battle and check if they feel the same. Often there's a common understanding.

Rap sends, you could argue is different to sending in itself. Look at MGK and Eminem as a perfect send receive reply example.

Rap beef I would consider would be your Trippie Redd Vs Takeshi beef. It goes outside of the music commonly for whatever reason. It's not exactly an easy form to study.

I would probably say Drake and Push is a rap sends situation, those usually evolve to rap beef. Sadly, he compares it to battling which in all honesty is more innocent from the inside than people understand it to be. He definitely ain't a battler if he ain't serving handshakes.

snippet.textDisplay: I think really the "rules" of rap you're talking about do exist though. Pusha crossed and line but at the same time he didn't. He dropped bars. Smart chess move on the reveal. But even in Battle Rap they have rules. Go watch Eminem's movie on battle rap. The dude crossed the line by revealing dude was a game designer, talked about his daughter needing support for her lungs. It's called being a human being. So if Pusha GENUINELY hates Drake, he's not going to respect the moralistic boundaries of being a human. So rules don't matter. That's BEEF. Not rap beef. Rappers beef over music all the time but there is a limit. I'm not going to talk about someone's dead relative if I'm trying to prove I'm a better lyricist. I'm going to try to out rap you. That's the point of MCing. Tory vs Joyner was the perfect example of how artist should take rap beef. Keep it to who makes better verses. Gain the recognition being better from the other artist fan base and keep it too the bars. Reveals are cool and all but MCing is lyricism and being able to manipulate words in a way many people can't. There are people who do it better than others. That's the point of the competition. Everyone eats, but I'm coming for #1.
